{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c463e0ae-0da6-4e7c-a83d-d971e67acaad","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter ref-safety scoping\n\nC# 15 tightens lifetime analysis for `scoped` ref structs. The collection expression `[x * 2]` targeting `Span<int>` uses implicit `stackalloc` — that memory's lifetime is the **loop body**. Assigning it to `results` (which lives outside the loop) is now a ref-safety error because the backing storage doesn't survive the iteration.\n\n**Fix:** Allocate once outside the loop:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    Span<int> results = stackalloc int[source.Length];\n    for (int i = 0; i < source.Length; i++)\n    {\n        results[i] = source[i] * 2;\n    }\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Metadata.cs` — `this` is invalid in attribute arguments\n\n`nameof` now supports unqualified instance member references in attributes, but **`this` itself is not available in an attribute context** (attributes are compile-time metadata with no instance). The explicit `this.` qualifier is the error.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the `this.`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` keyword ambiguity in collection expressions\n\nC# 15 expands the `with` keyword's role, making it reserved in more contexts. Inside a collection expression `[...]`, the parser now interprets `with(...)` as keyword syntax rather than a method call, creating a parse error.\n\n**Fix:** Escape the identifier with `@`, or (better) rename the method:\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: verbatim identifier\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n\n// Option B: rename (preferred — avoids future conflicts)\nobject combine(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [combine(x, y), z];\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"102cef6b-778c-491c-afdc-c4bf38b69f03","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningTe